{
  "texts": [
    "Recent advances in edge computing have enabled the deployment of large language models (LLMs) on distributed edge devices, reducing latency and enhancing privacy [1]- [5], [10], [11], [15], [17], [19].",
    "Several frameworks have attempted to decentralise AI capabilities for mobile, autonomous, or lowconnectivity settings [16], [18], [20], [23], [28].",
    "However, deploying resource-intensive LLMs in constrained environments poses non-trivial challenges in preserving model integrity and auditability.EdgeShard is a pioneering framework that partitions LLM computation across multiple edge devices, enabling collaborative inference while addressing bandwidth, compute, and trust constraints [1], [22], [27].",
    "The use of cryptographically verifiable logs further enables post-hoc auditability without compromising performance [24], [25], Despite these advances, distributed inference introduces unique risks such as silent model corruption, compromised shards, and unverifiable feedback signals.",
    "These challenges become more severe when the devices involved are heterogeneous, potentially adversarial, or lack consistent hardware reliability [16], [24]- [26], [31], [32]."
  ]
}